Adjust rack to middle position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Line a #baking sheet{} with foil and brush with @cooking oil{1%tsp} (or coat with nonstick spray). Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and thinly slice @onion{1}(halved, peeled and sliced thinly); mince a few slices until you have 1 TBSP.

Heat a drizzle of @olive oil{2%tsp} in a large pan over medium-high heat. Add sliced onion; cook for ~{3%minutes}.

Add @diced chicken thighs{10%oz} and @Southwest spice blend{1%tbsp}; cook, breaking up meat into pieces, until beef is browned and onion is softened, ~{4-6%minutes}.

> Chicken is fully cooked when internal temperature reaches 165°. Cook through this step as instructed, swapping in chicken (no need to break up into pieces!) or turkey for beef.

Stir in @Tex-Mex paste{1%unit} and 1/3 cup water. Simmer until mixture has thickened and beef is cooked through, ~{2-4%minutes} more. Turn off heat.

Meanwhile, drizzle @flour tortillas{6} with @olive oil{1%tbsp}; brush or rub to completely coat.

Place tortillas on a clean work surface. Once beef filling is done, add a heaping 1/4 cup filling to one side of each tortilla, then sprinkle each with 1 TBSP @Mexican cheese blend{1/2%cup}. Roll up tortillas, starting with filled sides, to create flautas. Place, seam sides down, on prepared baking sheet.

> Tip: Make sure the flautas are snug on the sheet—this will prevent them from unrolling.

Bake on middle rack until golden brown and crispy, ~{8-12%minutes}.

While flautas bake, finely dice @tomato{1}(finely diced). In a small #bowl{}, combine tomato and minced onion. Season with @salt{}.

Divide flautas between plates. Top with pico de gallo and @smoky red pepper crema{4%tbsp}. Serve.